  <!-- Change this to your post date -->

  <div class="post-body">

    <p>Choosing Land with a Natural Water Source – My First Priority. <br><br>
      When I started thinking about building my house, my first concern was simple: Does the land have a natural water source?<br>
      &nbsp&nbspHere in Kerala, the first thing most of us do after buying land is dig a well. It’s almost a tradition. The availability of water in the well tells us a lot about the land.
          
       <br>&nbsp&nbsp If the water level is not adequate, there’s always the option of a borewell. But honestly, borewell water tastes very different from the well water I grew up using.
        
        In our area, wells are usually full of water throughout the year, except during peak summer. <br>&nbsp&nbspHowever, things changed a bit after the floods a few years ago. The floods affected many natural water sources, including wells. Since then, it has become common practice to test well water in a lab before using it for drinking or cooking.
        
        <br> <br> Even with a good water source, purification is important. I want something that is
      <br> &nbsp * Sustainable
       <br>&nbsp * Not too expensive
      <br>&nbsp  * Easy to maintain
       
      <br><br>  Here are the types of purifiers based on their purification process.
       <br><Strong>1. UV/UF Purifier</Strong> 

<br>&nbsp&nbspThis is suitable if the water is already relatively clean.

<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Kills bacteria and viruses (UV)
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Removes impurities (UF)
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Does not change taste much
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Low maintenance

<br><br><strong>2. RO Purifier</strong>

<br>&nbsp&nbspUseful when water has high dissolved salts or contamination.

<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Removes heavy metals and dissolved impurities
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Makes water very safe
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* But can slightly change taste
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Wastes some water

<br><br><strong>3. Water Softener</strong>

<br>&nbsp&nbspThis is mainly for hard water issues.

<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Reduces hardness (good for skin, hair, and appliances)
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Usually used along with other purifiers
<br>&nbsp&nbsp* Not mainly for drinking water purification

<br><br>For me, having a natural water source is not just about convenience—it’s about connection to the land and long-term sustainability.
</p>

    <p>Choosing the right purifier depends on the quality of the water we get. So before buying anything, I plan to test the water first and then decide what suits best.
      
      <br><br>Purifiers are two types based on it need of power, Electric and Manual Purifiers.&nbspLet see if there is any difference in efficiency between these two categories.
      <br><br>&nbsp&nbsp<strong>Manual (Non-electric) purifier</strong>
     <br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp*It is a basic filter. 
<br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp*Good when your water is already fairly clean
<br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp*Cheap, simple, and eco-friendly
<br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp*But not strong enough for unsafe water

<br><br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbspIt is best for:
    <br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp  *Well water with good quality
 <br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp *Municipal supply
       <br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp*Budget-friendly homes
      
      <br><br>&nbsp&nbsp<strong>Electric purifier</strong>
      
 <br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbspThink of it as a complete water treatment system
 <br>&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp&nbspRemoves salt, chemicals, bacteria, everything
